---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="API Reference" activeSection="api">
  <h1>API Reference</h1>
  <p>The backend exposes a REST API at <code>http://localhost:8080</code> (default). All endpoints return JSON.</p>

  <h2>Endpoints</h2>

  <h3>GET /api/rules</h3>
  <p>Returns all available audit rules grouped by category, and all rule presets.</p>
  <pre><code>curl http://localhost:8080/api/rules | jq</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Response:</strong></p>
  <pre><code>{'{'}
  "categories": [
    {'{'}
      "key": "on-page",
      "label": "On-Page SEO",
      "rules": [
        {"{"} "key": "title_exists", "label": "Page has a &lt;title&gt; tag", "severity": "critical" {"}"}
      ]
    {'}'}
  ],
  "presets": [
    {'{'}
      "key": "full_scan",
      "label": "Full Scan",
      "description": "All 130+ checks for maximum coverage",
      "ruleKeys": ["title_exists", "..."]
    {'}'}
  ]
{'}'}</code></pre>

  <h3>POST /api/crawl</h3>
  <p>Start a new crawl job for a domain.</p>
  <pre><code>curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/crawl \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{'{'}
    "domain": "example.com",
    "maxPages": 100,
    "selectedRules": ["title_exists", "h1_count"]
  {'}'}'</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Request body:</strong></p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Field</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>domain</code></td><td>string</td><td>Required. Domain to crawl (e.g. <code>example.com</code> or <code>localhost:3000</code>)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>maxPages</code></td><td>number</td><td>Optional. Max pages to crawl. <code>0</code> = unlimited.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>selectedRules</code></td><td>string[]</td><td>Optional. Rule keys to run. Empty = all rules.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p><strong>Response:</strong></p>
  <pre><code>{'{'}
  "id": "uuid-of-the-crawl-job",
  "status": "queued"
{'}'}</code></pre>

  <h3>GET /api/crawl/:id/progress</h3>
  <p>Server-Sent Events stream for real-time crawl progress.</p>
  <pre><code>curl -N http://localhost:8080/api/crawl/&lt;job-id&gt;/progress</code></pre>
  <p>Events include page completion, page count, and final result data.</p>

  <h3>GET /api/report/:id</h3>
  <p>Get the full audit report for a completed crawl job.</p>
  <pre><code>curl http://localhost:8080/api/report/&lt;job-id&gt; | jq</code></pre>

  <h3>GET /api/report/:id/export/csv</h3>
  <p>Download the report as a CSV file.</p>
  <pre><code>curl -o report.csv http://localhost:8080/api/report/&lt;job-id&gt;/export/csv</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Query params:</strong> <code>?exclude=rule_key1,rule_key2</code> to omit specific rules.</p>

  <h3>GET /api/report/:id/export/md</h3>
  <p>Download the report as a Markdown file (AI-agent-friendly format).</p>
  <pre><code>curl -o report.md http://localhost:8080/api/report/&lt;job-id&gt;/export/md</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Query params:</strong> <code>?exclude=rule_key1,rule_key2</code> to omit specific rules.</p>

  <h3>GET /api/health</h3>
  <p>Health check endpoint.</p>
  <pre><code>curl http://localhost:8080/api/health</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Response:</strong> <code>{'{"status":"ok"}'}</code></p>

  <h2>Authentication</h2>
  <p>The API does not require authentication when running locally. All endpoints are accessible without tokens or API keys. If you deploy the server publicly, consider adding authentication middleware or placing it behind a reverse proxy with access controls.</p>

  <h2>Rate Limiting</h2>
  <p>There are no built-in rate limits on the API. The worker pool processes one crawl job at a time per worker (default: 2 workers). Additional crawl requests are queued and processed in order. The SSE progress stream is lightweight and suitable for long-polling clients.</p>

  <h2>Error Responses</h2>
  <p>All error responses follow this format:</p>
  <pre><code>{'{'}
  "error": "Human-readable error message"
{'}'}</code></pre>
  <p>Common HTTP status codes: <code>400</code> for invalid input, <code>404</code> for unknown job IDs, <code>500</code> for internal server errors.</p>

  <h2>Example: cURL</h2>
  <pre><code># Start a crawl
curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/crawl \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{'{'}
    "domain": "example.com"
  {'}'}'

# Get the report
curl http://localhost:8080/api/report/YOUR_JOB_ID

# Export as markdown
curl http://localhost:8080/api/report/YOUR_JOB_ID/export/md -o report.md</code></pre>
</DocsLayout>
